A few words in conclusion on the origin of the name Enthymeme. That its etymology is to be found in ἐν and θυμὸς, is undeniable3 but only in the same degree as is also true of ἐνθυμεῖσθαι, ἐνθύμιος, and other cognate terms. But that it has no special reference to a premise in the mind, is evident3 first, because θυμὸς in the Aristotelian phraseology is not “ the mind,” and has nothing to do with the expression or suppression of premises: secondly, because the word ἐνθύμημα occurs in writers earlier than Aristode, and before it could have assumed its technical meaning. To ascertain the true derivation, however, is not so eas)r as to refute a palpably absurd one. If, however, we were compelled to make a suggestion, the following, though not confidently put forward, has at least the merit of not being positively ridiculous. Ac- cording to the analogy of words of the same termination, Such as Φιλοσόφημα, ἐπιχείρημα, σόφισμα, διο. ἐνθύμημα will properly signify the result of an act of reflection¹¹.
